preneurs, and politicians debated Italy’s Chinese, Zhang argues that these stakeholders viewed the migration as a particularly effective example to support or dispute Italy’s general stance toward migrant integration and economic globalization. Zhang also proposes that an Italian-Chinese migrant cultural repertoire offered the stakeholders resources to cover the migration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChinesezItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aChinesezItalyxHistoryy21st century. 0aMass media and culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aChina.  aChinese.  aItaly.  acrime reporting.  acultural dialogue.  aculture.  adebates.  adiaspora.  aessentialism.  aethnocultural.  aimmigration to Italy.  amedia.  amigrant.  amigration.  anarratives.  arepertoire.  avictimhood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144263045140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442630451423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442630451.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles